Interestingly, Sindbis virus (SINV), an alphavirus lacking the YXXM motif in nsP3, failed to induce sustained AKT activation (

  Fig 5A
 ) and only caused a ~30% increase in glycolytic activity (measured as lactate over glucose ratio (

  Fig 5B
 )), compared to the ~100% increase observed for SFV. Importantly, while we measured a decrease in nucleotide concentrations (

  Fig 5C
 ), no decrease in choline and phosphocholine levels was observed upon SINV infection (

  Fig 5D
 ) and no changes were measured in the concentrations of myristic, palmitic or stearic acids in infected cells (

  Fig 5E
 ). Thus SINV, which does not rely on AKT hyperactivation during replication, may have evolved different mechanisms of metabolic activation and lipid use/synthesis. Inhibition of glycolysis (with 2DG) or of the PPP (with DHEA) caused similar degrees of inhibition of almost 1 log, suggesting that SINV relies on these two metabolic pathways (

  Fig 5F
 ).
